 With their exaggerated anaerobic capabilities, Hochachka's diving mammals, airbreathing fishes, and hypoxia-adapted lower vertebrates allow a detailed assessment of what can and what cannot be adjusted in the process of extending hypoxia tolerance. The book places the enzymatic and biochemical machinery firmly in the biological context and assumes only a modest familiarity with bioenergetics and metabolic biochemistry. The author's clear prose should make this technical presentation pleasantly unintimidating for any physiologist, biochemist, or clinical investigator. The insights of his unique approach make Living without Oxygen essential reading.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAdaptation, Physiological. 0aAnaerobiosis. 0aAnaérobiose. 0aAnoxemia. 0aAnoxia. 0aAnoxémie. 0aGlycolyse. 0aGlycolysis. 0aOxygen. 0aTiere (Zoologie). 4aAnaerobiosis. 4aAnoxemia. 4aGlycolysis. 4aOxygen -- Physiological effect. 4aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Science eBook Packagez9783110353549oZDB-23-HSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067449825940uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067449826640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674498266423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674498266/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-HSP